Step 1: Import data

One of the most common file types data analysts import into R is comma separated values files, or .csv files. The tidyverse library package readr has a number of functions for “reading in” or importing data, including .csv files and other external sources.

In the chunk below, use the read_csv() function to import data from the .csv files in the project folder called “Bike_trips_original_27_06_2021” and save it as a data frame called bike_trip_2020_june_imported . Similarly all the data for different months(June 2020-May 2021) are imported and saved in the respective data frame.

The results will display as column specifications:

bike_trip_2020_june_imported <- read_csv("~/Desktop/Case study/Bike_trips_original_27_06_2021/csv_files_2021_06_27_version1_original/2020_june.csv")

Step 4: Analyze Data

Here we are combining the cleaned data from multiple .csv cleaned files to a single .csv file

Bike_trips_merge_12_months<-bind_rows(
  bike_trip_2020_june_imported_clean ,
  bike_trip_2020_july_imported_clean,
  bike_trip_2020_august_imported_clean,
  bike_trip_2020_sept_imported_clean ,
  bike_trip_2020_oct_imported_clean,
  bike_trip_2020_nov_imported_clean,
  bike_trip_2020_dec_imported_clean,
  bike_trip_2021_jan_imported_clean,
  bike_trip_2021_feb_imported_clean ,
  bike_trip_2021_march_imported_clean,
  bike_trip_2021_april_imported_clean ,
  bike_trip_2021_may_imported_clean
  )
View(Bike_trips_merge_12_months)
write.csv(Bike_trips_merge_12_months,"bike_trips_12_months.csv",row.names = FALSE)

  summarize(number_of_ride=n(),.groups = 'drop')

bike_trip_2020_analysed<- read_csv("~/Desktop/Case study/bike_trips_12_months.csv")
## 
## ── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## cols(
##   ride_id = col_character(),
##   rideable_type = col_character(),
##   started_at = col_character(),
##   ended_at = col_character(),
##   start_station_name = col_character(),
##   end_station_name = col_character(),
##   member_casual = col_character(),
##   ride_length = col_time(format = ""),
##   day_of_week = col_character(),
##   month_of_ride = col_character()
## )
rides_one_year<-bike_trip_2020_analysed %>%
  group_by(month_of_ride,member_casual) %>%
  summarize(number_of_ride=n(),.groups = 'drop') 
ggplot(data = rides_one_year,aes(x =month_of_ride,y=number_of_ride))+
  geom_point(aes(color=member_casual,shape=member_casual))+
   labs(title="Comparison between Months and Number of rides for Casual and Member riders",
       x="Months",
       y="Number of rides")
